# Dive Core Concepts

## Project
A project is a collection of modules, configurations, and resources that define what you want to accomplish. Projects typically:
- Live in version control
- Can be deployed to multiple environments
- Define all resources needed to run
- Contain configuration for different environments

## Environment
An environment is a running instance of a project. It contains:
- Active module instances
- Running executions
- Current state of all resources
- Environment-specific configuration

Common environments include Production, Staging, and Development.

## Module
A self-contained, reusable collection of Dive resources that can be instantiated and run. Similar to Terraform modules, a Dive module:
- Has defined inputs and outputs
- Contains one or more workflows and their associated resources
- Can be composed with other modules
- Can be versioned and shared
- Defines its own resources (documents, tables, agents)

## Workflow
- A template for a repeatable process
- Has defined inputs and outputs
- Can be triggered manually or automatically
- Can invoke other workflows (supporting composition)
- Each workflow execution is tracked independently

## Task
- An individual unit of work within a workflow
- Defines a specific action or operation
- Can be executed by agents
- Has defined inputs and outputs
- Can be synchronous or asynchronous

## Execution
- Represents a single run of a workflow
- Has a unique identifier
- Maintains state and history
- Tracks task completions
- Records inputs and outputs
- Can spawn sub-executions for nested workflows

## Agent
- AI agents that perform tasks within workflows
- Defined within modules
- Have defined capabilities and roles
- Maintain their own memory
- Can access module resources
- Can be specialized for specific types of tasks

## Resources

### Documents
- Store structured and unstructured data
- Defined within modules
- Can be inputs to or outputs from workflows
- Versioned and trackable

### Tables
- Structured data storage
- Defined within modules
- Queryable by agents and workflows
- Support CRUD operations

### Memory
- Persistent context for specific agents
- Scoped to individual agents
- Supports agent learning and adaptation
- Can be cleared or preserved

### Triggers
- Event-based workflow initiators
- Can be time-based (schedules)
- Can respond to external events
- Can watch for resource changes

### Integrations
- Connections to external systems
- Both incoming and outgoing
- Can trigger workflows
- Can be used by tasks
